<subSubSection box="[899,1416,303,327]" pageId="1" pageNumber="660" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[839,1482,303,1951]" box="[899,1416,303,327]" pageId="1" pageNumber="660">This is the first karyotype description for</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="660" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[839,1482,303,1951]" pageId="1" pageNumber="660">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blyth" authorityYear="1844" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="660" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lepidus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="660">Rhinolophus lepidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
,
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="660" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[839,1482,303,1951]" pageId="1" pageNumber="660">
which is widely distributed in Asia from Afghanistan to China, as well as in Sumatra [
<bibRefCitation author="Levan A &amp; Fredga K &amp; Sandberg A." box="[846,879,403,427]" editor="Wilson DE &amp; Reeder DM" journalOrPublisher="Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press" pageId="1" pageNumber="660" part="2005" refId="ref3691" refString="26. Simmons NB. Order Chiroptera. In: Wilson DE, Reeder DM, eds. Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference, 3 rd ed. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press; 2005: 312 - 529." title="Simmons NB. Order Chiroptera" type="journal volume" volumeTitle="Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference, 3 rd" year="1964">26</bibRefCitation>
]. The karyotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blyth" authorityYear="1844" box="[1117,1228,403,427]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="660" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lepidus">
<emphasis box="[1117,1135,404,427]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="660">R</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1151,1228,403,427]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="660">lepidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Hainan Island was 2n = 62 and FN = 60 (
<figureCitation box="[1150,1215,436,460]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[156,236,1681,1706]" captionTargetBox="[249,1384,513,1648]" captionTargetId="figure-151@2.[244,1388,501,1653]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1 Conventional (A), G-banding (B), and C-banding karyotypes of Rhinolophus lepidus from Hainan Island, China. Secondary constrictions are indicated by arrows." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4266206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4266206/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="660">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), consisting of 30 medium-sized to small acrocentric autosomal pairs, a large subtelocentric X chromosome, and a small acrocentric Y chromosome. Secondary constrictions were detected adjacent to one pair of medium-sized acrocentric chromosomes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
